  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>Risks & Limitations</h2>

  <h3>Upside risks</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Refining Margins:</strong> Extended periods of high crack spreads due to tight global refining capacity.</li>
    <li><strong>Aggressive Buybacks:</strong> MPC frequently retires shares rapidly, accelerating per-share value growth.</li>
    <li><strong>Asset Spinoffs:</strong> Restructuring or monetization of midstream (MPLX) assets.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Cyclicality:</strong> Refining margins can collapse during economic downturns, destroying cash flows.</li>
    <li><strong>Regulation & Transition:</strong> Environmental regulations and the long-term energy transition away from fossil fuels.</li>
    <li><strong>Capital Intensity:</strong> Heavy maintenance capex and turnaround costs can suppress FCF unexpectedly.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why use DCF for a cyclical refiner?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">While earnings and P/E ratios swing wildly based on crack spreads, long-term Free Cash Flow generation smoothed over a multi-year period gives the best approximation of core value creation.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Where do the discount and growth rates come from?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">They are strictly derived mathematically from current fixed-income yields (10Y Treasury at 4.18%) and actual company historical CAGR, eschewing arbitrary or fabricated assumptions.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Does this account for the MPLX stake?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">The consolidated cash flows from operations include distributions from MPLX. However, complex sum-of-the-parts valuations are beyond the scope of this pure consolidated DCF.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

